Sensors (latest)
Shows the current system state coming from the “world”: the latest telemetry reading per machine/metric (e.g., temperature, vibration).
This is the “input layer” for rule reasoning.

Rule feed (live)
A chronological log of what the rule engine is doing: every time a rule fires, it appears here with the simulated time.
This helps you verify chaining/CEP behavior and understand “why did this happen now?”.

Anomalies
These are higher-level diagnoses derived from raw sensor states/events.
Example: “Potential bearing failure” is created when conditions like high temperature + high vibration co-occur (your Level 2 reasoning).

Interventions
These are recommended actions / priorities derived from anomalies + context (e.g., main line vs not).
This is Level 3 reasoning: “Given the anomaly, what should we do and how urgent is it?”

Safety
This is the engine answering the query “is it safe for the next 24h?” based on component health + service intervals, updated over time.
In the overall system, it’s the “decision/assessment” output parallel to interventions.


